< Text>
Clean Facility, Convenient Location and Responsive staff!

From finding an amazing deal online, to checking in and moving out, my experience was top notch! Rick is professional, engaging and incredibly supportive as the onsite manager.

I moved from San Lorenzo Village while closing escrow on my new home. I needed storage fast and nearby. I prefer to support local businesses. The other facility I used previously is still a favorite of mine, however I was happy to try out Extra Space Storage due to their proximity to my location, plus they‚Äôre located in San Lorenzo!

I went online and found an amazing online only pricing, that saved me $80 per month and gave me the first month free on a 10x30 space.

When I went in to talk to Rick and secure the space, he gives the marketing spiel, and then tells me in the end that my final pricing which is what drew me in is better than what he could do in house. (Well yea that‚Äôs why I‚Äôm here!)

The space is slightly smaller than 10x30 by 5-6‚Äù both LxW. Not a deal breaker for me, but I did notice it and also the other storage facility space (near the Hilton Garden Inn) is also higher. Still I wasn‚Äôt going to be packing the space to the gills so it worked for me.

My house finally closed escrow and I was able to move out over Labor Day weekend meaning I wasn‚Äôt going to use the whole month. When I gave my thirty day notice, yes you need to do that, again Rick worked with me to prorate my rent so I wasn‚Äôt paying the entire month. That was a blessing and completely unexpected! Moving and Buying a home can drain your wallet faster than a kid at Game Stop! So to save some cash along the way is truly appreciated!

Their hours for accessing your space are 08:00 -10:00 pm. Seven days a week. They‚Äôre located at the very end of Grant Street in the Industrial area of San Lorenzo, near the Bay Shoreline Trail. When you get sick of schlepping all your stuff around you can take a nice stroll along the Bay! And when it‚Äôs time to move, you‚Äôre easily accessible to the 880 South freeway on ramp at the other end. The 238 and 880 North on ramp is only 1.3 Miles from Extra Space.

I had a great experience for my very short term stay and highly recommend them for your storage needs. Go check them out and say Hi to Rick for me! -Vanessa<//Text>

< name>
Dave C<//name>
<date>1574463320567</date><Rate>5<//Rate><Review>This is definitely worth checking out. There are only a handful of tents to get food, so it's understandable if the lines are long, but the wait is worth it. Check out "Boffo Cart", dark brown tent halfway down the block between Washington and Clay. Their Chopped Pork is great! I've had it a few times by now. The pork is extremely flavorful and the bread isn't enough that'll put you in a food coma after lunch. The wait is very reasonable. The Muffaletta is good too.
The produce around covers about 3-4 blocks. There are a few tents for florists, a couple for breads, live music at the intersection of Washington & 9th. Every farmer's market has kettle corn. You can get almonds/walnuts, spreads for breads, eggs, strawberries and other fruit.< /Review>< pics>

<UserId.>115077903758063756274< /UserId.><user_name>Megan Brownlee</user_name>< Date>
1600378431369< /Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate><review>Beach Cities Management is a remarkable rental company and I would highly recommend them for anyone seeking an apartment in Southern California. I first rented with Beach Cities Management in 2017. Anyone who has tried to find rental units in Los Angeles and Orange County is likely aware of how stressful the process is. However, Viviana at Beach Cities Management was incredibly communicative, and worked with my partner and I to make sure that we could find a rental unit and move in as seamlessly as possible. Viviana was incredibly responsive to any maintenance need or concern we had through the duration time in the unit, and during the move out process, she worked with us to make sure that everything was taken care of.

The only reason that I left the unit was due to a move out of Southern California. Fast forward two years, I had to plan a move back the Los Angeles area. Because I had such a positive experience renting with Beach Cities (and particularly working with Viviana), I reached out to Beach Cities to ask about available rentals. < review>
Very Misleading Company. Dustin has been insulting and degrading to my wife and I. I have been renting with this company for less than 4 months. There have been so many discrepancies between what they promise and what they actually provide that I am only left with believing they are deceitful or incompetent. Either way- Not the best company to deal with. There are plenty others to look at first.

When we first wanted to rent, we asked if they could put a lockbox on the house advertised so we could see the place. They did and we loved it. When we went to sign the lease. they said rent was actually several hundred dollars more a month and the place I wanted was actually the back house. I asked them why the lockbox was placed on the front house and why the picture shows the front house and they told us we must have been confused. Strike 1.

We decided to walk and not rent the place. They called us back shortly and said they would honor the price advertised. I was happy about that but I did wonder how often they pull this game in hopes to squeeze more rent out of tenants. They also told us all utilities are included. The day we moved in we realized gas was not on. Turns out they also changed their mind about that. If we had known about this prior to moving in we could have ordered gas. But because we were told all utilities included we did not schedule an appointment to turn on gas. That meant me, my wife, and my two small children spent the next two weeks living without heat or hot water while we waited for our gas appointment. Strike 2.

For a while - they did offer a coupon on yelp. The deal was that I could buy a $200 voucher with Beach Cities Management for only $100. Guess what happens when I try to redeem the coupon? Dustin says the coupon was not meant for me. He comes up with excuse after excuse why he can't honor the coupon- he tells me his is a small business, he says the money would have to come out of his own pocket, he says have you ever seen anyone have a deal like this, he tries to guilt trip me, and insults me in effort to not honor the coupon. Never does he man up and take responsibility. Strike 3 and they are out. Find another company.

Dustin- if you are reading this and wish to apologize for the way you spoke to my wife and also honor the deal you made with me, then I will delete this review. I already deleted a review on Strikes 1 and 2 after he called me to complain about how this would hurt his business. But don't go guilt tripping my wife and try to convince her why we shouldn't use the coupon we bought and paid for. Don't blame me for all of the problems around this. Take responsibility and apologize.</review>

< Review>
We had called ahead of time and spoke to someone about our situation. My BF was going to rent a car down in the SD location so he can get to and from work the next day and I was going to lend him my car later in the evening so he has something to use for a longer period. The plan was for me to return his rental at my local OC location on my way home from dropping off my car to him while his car gets fixed. It didn't make sense for me to drop off my car to him in SD and have him take me back home in OC only to drive another 2 hours to go back home so we decided to get a rental for a day so he can go to work early and I can drop off my car later and drive the rental home and return it at a local Budget. I couldn't be with him tonight to be added on as a driver, but I've been able to drop by any Enterprise offices to be added on as a driver or add others as drivers whenever we needed a rental so I told him to check if we can do that with Budget.

He called a number he found online for Budget Car Rental at the John Wayne Airport location. He spoke to someone about whether I can go to the Budget office in OC to show ID to be added as a driver while he picked up the car at the SD location and he was told that was possible. After getting the greenlight I made plans to stop by the John Wayne Airport location and timed it when he would be at the SD location to get the logistics out of the way and save me any stress tomorrow.

Surprise, surprise when I arrived at the Avis office (Budget is at Avis) at John Wayne Airport I was told my BF has to be present for me to be added on as a driver. I had his confirmation number and explained he was in SD picking up the car now and I plan on returning it at the OC location tomorrow and they can speak to him to get whatever they need. I can understand their concerns that they can be speaking to anyone over the phone that will instruct them to add me on as a driver, but my BF was present at the SD location while I was at the OC location and it is asinine that company supervisors at each location cannot speak directly to each other to confirm both of our identity and obtain authorization for me to simply be added. The supervisor at the OC location was extremely flippant and argumentative that my BF didn't speak to him when he called the Budget/Avis office so it wasn't his problem my BF had a conversation with someone that told us I can be added as a driver at my local office to save us time tomorrow. He acted like my BF was mistaken and talked to the wrong company. Why would we waste our time and efforts and make up some story? Someone with the company needs to update listed phone numbers online because we called and spoke to someone at Budget. There was a logical fix and they were unaccomodating. Extremely poor customer service.<//Review>

< name>
Steve Nipps</name>
< text>
Low ratings can serve as a deterrent for people who plan on using a business or visiting a place, but it's not uncommon for people to have a 5-star experience at a lowly rated place or a 1-star experience at a highly rated place. I was initially turned off by the 2-star rating of Budget at SNA on Yelp, but being a Fastbreak member, I decided to try my luck here when planning a week-long socially-distanced road trip to Utah. Frankly speaking, I wasn't disappointed one bit and had yet another awesome 5-star experience with Budget!

I'm thankful for the kind and helpful staff at Budget SNA for entertaining my request for an AWD when I stated upfront that I was heading to the snowy mountains. After a brief wait, they handed me the keys for a smart Chevrolet Equinox 4x4, and that made our long drive so very comfortable. We were totally carefree when venturing out onto the snow-laden roads of Bryce Canyon NP and Zion NP in this beast!

I also appreciate Budget's prompt response and great customer service after I encountered a flat tire due to a tack when near Bryce Canyon NP. Their road side assistance staff were very helpful, and, when I informed the agent that would not be possible for me to replace the flat tire with the spare tire, and then drive on the spare tire to reach  any Budget locations to get a replacement vehicle before they close, the Budget agent mentioned that as an alternative approach I should get the flat tire replaced with¬†the spare, then get the flat tire fixed and re-fit for my drive from UT to CA. The kind agent mentioned that Budget will then cover up to $50 for road-side assistance for flat tire replacement with the spare, and up to $200 for repair and replacement of the flat tire. True to their word, upon furnishing the receipts, Budget refunded me the costs that I had to bear to get the flat tire fixed.

Overall, a fantastic auto rental experience with Budget despite the flat tire that cut short my travel at the start of the year.</text>

<review>For my week-long stay in Orange County, I needed a rental car and decided to go with Budget based on the prices and selection they were offering on their website.  My selection was for a Ford Focus ‚Äúor similar‚Äù, since this would have been adequate for my needs; I prefer to drive a small car but needed one with with 4 doors and a good amount of trunk space.  On 7/3/19 my reservation was confirmed, for which I received a further confirmation/reminder on 7/5.
Upon my arrival, what was offered to me was a Volkswagen Beetle, a 2-door.  I knew that accommodating my luggage and passenger needs in a 2-door would have been very difficult, and said so to the representative who was helping me.  Instead of giving me any other options within the category I had selected, he immediately proceeded to upsell me to a full-size car, which ended up being a Toyota Camry.  He did not offer any other suggestions in the compact, economy, standard or mid-size price categories, so I was stuck.  I realize that I was not guaranteed a Ford Focus exactly, but the crux of my issue with with this scenario is the misleading phrase ‚Äúor similar‚Äù.  Practically, I do not consider a 2-door to be ‚Äúsimilar‚Äù to a 4-door.  And besides, the specs listed for the car I reserved distinctly specified that the car, whatever make-model, would be in fact a 4-door; to me that's false advertising, plain & simple.
In addition, here‚Äôs what I find especially interesting: going back to the Budget website and comparing prices for compact vs. standard/full-size cars, the difference is not $11 per day, which is what I was charged for the upgrade.  The difference, as advertised on the website, is $10 TOTAL for a week-long rental.  So, even adjusting for the upgrade in car category, exactly why was I paying an extra $67 suddenly?  And the salesperson who helped me was not the lone con artist, his coworker was in on the ruse and pulled some magical strings to make me believe that he was giving me a deal.  What a despicable racket.  I don't know how people who do business in this way can live with themselves.
This was a transparent bait-and-switch scenario.  I feel that Budget took advantage of me and ripped me off.  I should have gone straight to another rental car counter, but after a day of flying & running around, I did not have the time nor energy for going through the rigmarole of trying to get my money back and starting over, especially since I knew that my prospects of getting a reasonable deal elsewhere for the 4th of July weekend were not good (I suspect the salesman who was helping me was acutely aware of this also, and that may indicate a crucial element of their sales tactics in general).
The car itself was fine, and there were no other issues.  However, based on my experience, my word of caution to those who choose to rent from Budget is that if you purchase online, what you can expect is to be misled and massively upsold at the counter, and what you can‚Äôt expect is to end up with what was originally advertised to you, and any apparent price difference that led you to choose Budget over the others will be promptly made up for, and then some -- for a low-cost option, go with Alamo; they have never given me any such trouble.

Needless to say, I will not be renting from Budget again, and I will dutifully steer anyone who asks my advice in almost any other direction.  (As a final note, since this experience I have tried contacting them several times about my complaints and after more than a week have received no response at all.)<//review>< pics>

< review>
This place is absolutely horrible. My wife made all the reservations and prepaid for a car for four days. We got off the plane with two kids and wound up waiting in line for 30 minutes behind a whopping two people. Behind the counter, two people were chatting on the phone while one incompetent fool was helping customers. I was amazed at his ability to handle this position at all given his very limited grasp of the English language. When it was our turn, we were offered every rip-off feature possible from extra insurance to gas packages.  We declined every single thing he offered. I remember getting tired of saying "No" over and over again. After this ordeal, I was asked for my credit card so that they could put a $100 hold on it for damages and what not. I was assured this would be refunded twice. After returning the car four days later and returning home, I checked my bank account and noticed I had been charged $165. I called them to ask what had happened and was told that I had opted for insurance and that was why. I looked over my bill more closely and damn, it did say I accepted insurance for $9/day. I explained that I had declined that and that either way, $9 times 4 equals only $36 not $165. She became agitated and said their were other "undisclosed charges" that I agreed to. I stated that I had declined everything. At this point, she basically told me to "F" off and hung up. After my early morning flight into John Wayne airport (flying southwest... you know how that is üôÑ I will soon learn that was not the first mistake of my day) I found relief when I was immediately greeted by what I thought was the Budget Rental Car booth. It looked like a booth. Had 4 walls like a booth. A sign that said Budget... by God it must be the Budget booth.

I walk over, so happy that it was only a 5 minute walk from the gate, only to be greeted by a sign that said ‚ÄúBudget Rental Downstairs.‚Äù I sigh to myself, but think ‚Äî oh, okay, downstairs. No big deal. Little did I know that ‚Äúdownstairs‚Äù actually means 26.2 miles through John Wayne airport. After my airport marathon, I make it to the makeshift booth. Aka the Budget Dungeon. No air conditioning; barely any light; could hardly move in there.

When I squeezed inside, I see two representivies. I was surprised to see another customer survive the marathon... once Nicole, who I will have the pleasure of working with in a matter of seconds, finished with the first victim, I was next on the chopping block.

Unknowing of my upcoming sentence, I walk up to Nicole without any greeting ‚Äî no expression on her face and to be quite honest with you, I didn‚Äôt know if she was real or not...

Nicole: ‚Äúlast 4‚Äù

0x80dcdeedec1a53fb:0xc2617312806ae142< /GmapID>
< Review>
Furious. I will NEVER be using Budget again...

I rented my car through Priceline for a week, because my car was stolen.

My car was recovered the next day, so I called the reservation hotline.

This is exactly what I said: "I rented my car on Priceline, and I would like to know if I return my car early, if you will refund the difference
from what I already paid." The gentleman (super sweet man, sounded
Persian maybe, said his name was Alan) said that I would be able to. He couldn't
give me details, but he said that I would have to check with the counter
when I returned the car at John Wayne.

At John Wayne, I checked with the young lady (again, very sweet brunette
girl), and she said that I would be refunded from Priceline, but there
was nothing that she could do as Priceline is a 3rd party vendor. This
made sense. So I rolled out.

Now, of course, Priceline says that a deal is a deal, and that since I
prepaid, they are not going to refund anything. I mean, come on. Is that
fair and in the contract? It is. But I never would have gone through
with returning the car 5 days early if I had not been instructed by two
separate employees at Budget that I would receive a refund from
Priceline.

So I ask you, how is it that both of Budget's employees prompted me to
return the car and go to Priceline for a refund? I can't tell if this
was an unethical move or an ignorant move, but neither is forgivable.

My position is that this is not a fair way to treat customers. I
understand that Budget's counterpoint is that, "Rules are rules", but is
that really any way to treat the people who rent from you? Ultimately,
why should I not receive a refund or a credit for the 5 unused days? $173 for a
Sunday at 1pm to Tuesday at 1pm rental? Come on. Again, I never would have returned the car if I had not been instructed to do so by 2 employees at Budget.

<review>Terrible experience with this company!!
We rented a car at this location (SNA - John Wayne Airport, Orange County CA)  through the Priceline website and when we arrived, we were given a list of cars we were told were in the same class to choose from.  No upgrade charges were EVER discussed.  The desk agent then had my husband initial for insurance coverage.  Again, upgrade charges were never mentioned or discussed.  Unfortunately, my husband initialed an area that authorized an upgrade, thinking it was for the insurance.  We were charged an ADDITIONAL $429 when our credit card bill arrived!  They denied that we weren't told the car was an upgrade and the company (after 3 days worth of phone calls to corporate) would not even compromise on the bill.  This was after the first representative I spoke with offered to remove half of the charge.  The corporate supervisor vetoed that, saying she (the first representative I spoke with) wasn't authorized. Honesty and integrity seems to be a consistent issue at this company  :(
Finally spoke with a supervisor at the SNA location, who was uncooperative and stated that she "could never imagine" her employee making any error (Wow!).  That she's sure he would have explained all the charges and she was not willing to compromise the charges in any way whatsoever and in fact "couldn't".  However, Budget's Corporate offices stated to me directly that any refund would have to come from the actual location, but that they had refused to give one when asked.  So, yet another untruth.  I guess that means that we, the customers are lying, as he (Budget's employee) absolutely did not mention any upgrade charges.  There is NO WAY we would have ever paid an extra $50 per day for a rental car we bid for on priceline to pay only $20 per day. <name>Clayton Thiel<//name><Date>1498588744802</Date><rate>5</rate><Text>I've been using Aurora for about a month now, and it is by far the best design/quote software i have ever used. Not perfect, but pretty close in my opinion. While it is the most expensive software we have used of this kind, the ease of use (once you grasp the nuances of the program), quality of the end product, and customer service make up for it.

Pros:
-quick, can do a full proposal in under 15min
-great 3D models
-shading tool is very helpful
-energy modelling is very accurate compared to our proven (much more time consuming) methods
-EXCELLENT customer support, they have always gotten back to me quickly on any concern
-intuitive, I found any time I have said "it would be great if the program could do this", the program can. Simple things like copying modules are very simple
-very customizable proposals

Cons:
-expensive, especially if you go with the highest level, more than twice the cost of competitors product.  Being in Canada we don't have the benefit of Lidar, which was the biggest seller for the upgrade
-a bit of a learning curve to fully understand the program (however customer service is great at offering 1on1 training sessions to help with any issues)</Text><pictures>None</pictures>< response>

I go here every summer. The food is good, for camp food, and some tastes like it could be form a restaurant. I‚Äôve gone to Sherwood and Buccaneer camps here, though I liked Buccaneer better. The cabins at Sherwood are nice, although a little cramped. The activities are good, although you don‚Äôt have free access to the challenge courses during free time. Buccaneer was great. The activities are awesome, we always had access to the challenge courses (which I highly recommend), and the games were amazing. Shiver me Timber‚Äôs is a great game, and I wish I could play it every day.My only complaint with Buccaneer is that there isn‚Äôt any real toilets or at the campsite, and there aren‚Äôt any showers remotely close. You have to walk all the way down the hill to take a shower!  Some of the campfire songs are bad, but some are great.  I would highly recommend Westminster Woods for anyone that is thinking about going. This is a great experience and you should try!<//Review>

<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Food was excellent!! I have very high standards being  in a family where my Great Aunt had an Italian Restaurant for over 30 yrs and those recipes were followed by my parents. We picked 3 different dishes Classic Meat Lasagna (it was a huge portion with a delicacy hard to explain), Cannelloni Tricolore ( Fresh made Pasta with 3 sauces Marinara,Alfredo,Pesto), Seafood Risotto (Large portion of Risotto,huge Prawns, Scallops with a Lobster Reduction. We shared a portion with each other. Portions are large so worked out great. Everyone was happy with the food. We also had 3 children and they have a great priced kids menu. The choices are plenty. Then a Dessert Menu with a great selection. We also picked 3 items but being so stuffed got them to go. Our waitress was so wonderful and the atmosphere quaint with some Frank Sinatra and friends playing in the background. This restaurant was featured on Diners, Drive-In and Dives.< /Review>

<time>1608505491284</time>< Text>
Like all restaurants in Carmel right now, it's takeout only. Little Napoli menu can still be ordered from, but the food is prepared at their sister restaurant Vesuvio, a couple of blocks away. We ordered pasta last night and very much enjoyed the food. Times are tough for restaurants right now, so supporting them with take out orders is the only thing keeping them afloat, and with the quality of their food, Little Napoli/Vesuvio deserves to survive the shutdown. Eat local, and help your good restaurants<//Text>

<user_id>103742819485008958293</user_id>< text>
We stopped in one afternoon during "Car week".  The staff was all very friendly and pretty attentive towards our needs.  We ordered the spaghetti with meatballs and the lasagna.  Both were fantastic and I would recommend either to anyone. I did take off a star for the pricing. I understand this area is known for being a little pricey and we read through the previous reviews before we went in and that lead me to believe it wasn't quite this over inflated. Maybe we were paying "event pricing".< /text>

<UserId.>107802058118069961657< /UserId.><username>Heliana Mano< /username>< Date>
1508196011469<//Date>
< Rating>
3<//Rating>
< Review>
3.5 stars is where I stand.

Pretty big place and very busy. We stopped here for lunch as we reached Carmel back in August. It was busy but we waited for a bit and then got seated. Table for 6 was quite small for all of us so we had to watch our elbows while eating which was tad uncomfortable.

Only 1 bathroom for the entire restaurant which was located at the wine tasting room next to it. Horrible way to make your customers suffer :( I wasn't pleased.

Liked the decor around and service was good.

Food was decent. I liked all the items we tried but by no means this was authentic Italian cuisine. Italian recipes served for American diners with heavy and creamy sauces. But, we did have a great time overall no doubt about it. I felt overall food in Carmel was like this, touristy and heavy, not authentic, which is a little sad.

Between the 6 of us we shared:

- beet salad
- famous garlic bread
- gilroy roasted garlic plate
- mushroom pizza
- spaghetti alio oglio
- salmon over tagliatelle and asparagus
- veal osso buco ravioli
- lasagna

All entres were good but nothing exceptional. In fact, too heavy eventhough everything was shared between us so we all just had 1 bite of everything. Pastas were good but heavy on the cream kind of scene though I thought my veal ravioli was the best choice.

Overall, good scene if you're in a large group and looking for a good meal out. But not your Italian authentic scene sadly.<//Review>

Little Napoli menu can still be ordered from, but the food is prepared at their sister restaurant Vesuvio, a couple of blocks away. We ordered pasta last night and very much enjoyed the food. 111675023387548663913</user_id>
< Name>
Joseph Chargin, V<//Name>
< Time>
1547746583744< /Time>
<Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
I popped in here with a friend for lunch on a Monday. There was no host in sight, but the only other couple in the restuarant said they were told wherever was fine, so we took their advice and grabbed a window seat that looked out to a courtyard. Right when we sat down, a server appeared with the menus and the wine list. He allowed us to look over the menu and we decided to get the calamari with a chipotle aioli to begin. For our main plates, I ordered the Spicy cioppino rosso and my friend ordered the chicken parmesan with pappardelle.
The calamari came out after a few minutes and it was very good and the plate had a nice hearty portion on it. Crispy and light breading and the squid itself was not overdone. The aioli complemented the squid well and offered a kick while not being overpowering.
Then, our main plates arrived. My cioppino was delicious and as advertised, somewhat spicy. I say it was somewhat spicy because I have a low tolerance for heat. Nonetheless, all of the seafood was prepared wonderfully, nothing was rubbery or overdone. My friend's chicken parmesan was apparently delightful because she inhaled it while I was talking! From what I saw, the chicken came with a red sauce and was pablo breaded. The pappardelle came with a cream sauce.
All in all, we spent a decent amount of time at the restaurant and the server was polite and attentive as always kept our drinks refilled.< /text>

<rate>2<//rate>< review>
Was very excited to eat here per the recommendation of our resort concierge and after the restaurant had been on Diners, Drive Ins, and Dives. Great atmosphere and space, however the food was quite underwhelming especially for the price. At $180 to $200 for 4 people would expect exquisite flavor in the sauce and world famous garlic bread, but it was extremely average. The entrees were the perfect size but they once again lacked flavor and freshness of the ingredients. Overall, this would be a great meal if I was at home and paying $10 to $15 per entree, but regardless of the location and atmosphere this eatery disappointed in the most important category, the food.<//review>

<Time>1574774390845</Time>< review>
I dined on Hobo Stew, a Gorgonzola salad, and a glass of a Napa red called Vesuvius. Excellent. The stew was the highlight, with tender braised beef, onions, potatoes, leeks, carrots, etc., in a very nice savory gravy.  Good recommendations by the lady waiting the table. Has a nice, cozy atmosphere, with Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin in the background. Carmel, CA is such a nice place to walk and window shop and dine, just off the highway, much warmer than I expected.<//review>

Emmanuel Thioux</user_name>
< resp>
None< /resp>
< Review>
I actually wanted to go to La Bicyclette, but the 2 hours wait wasn't super enticing.

Little Napoli ended up being really good. I took the veal raviolis with mushroom cream sauce (pictured) and that was delicious. I'm not a fan of mushrooms but I must admit that the sauce was excellent. The portion was on point too.

I got the Pepe garlic bread, which was also really good.

I'd give it 5 stars if not for the fact that the place is somewhat pricey. I got a limoncello based cocktail that was $12 and the deserts, which I skipped were $9 minimum. The raviolis we about $18 but that, I didn't mind at all since they were so tasty.

I don't regret not going to the French restaurant across the street, and if you're looking for a good lunch, little Napoli is the place to go</Review>

< review>
In a an area of town filled with Italian joints, we found this very small, family run (maybe they all are?) stop thats been managed by the same lady for 30 years. Homemade pasta is the specialty, and you can taste the difference. Our kids raved. The service is quick and friendly, like a household feel to it. Reasonable prices as well, with a nice wine selection to boot.<//review>

< text>
We've been wanting to try Little Napoli for awhile but since it's quite a distance from where we live it's been kinda difficult. We finally had an excuse to make a trip up here so we decided to make a little detour.
Since we don't know when or if we'll be back, I told my sister let's splurge a little. We were both down with that! We ordered the garlic bread, arancini risotto lollipops and meatballs lollipops for appetizers. I wanted to try the PepeCello Spritz, probably shouldn't have ordered it since I had a cough but hey lemon cures everything and it was good! The meatballs were delicious, risotto lollipops were good but since I'm not a big of veggies that's all I could taste, garlic bread was ok I would have liked more garlic but that's just me.
I ordered classic Meat Lasagna, my sister the Cannelloni Tricolore. The lasagna was nice and cheesy but what took away from the flavor was the fact that is was a little burnt at the bottom so that sucked. The Cannelloni was good though, I especially loved the pesto sauce out of the three sauces that it came with. We decided to take a dish with us to the hotel, oh man we're already planning a return visit just for this. The Peppery Hobo Stew! Even I ate the veggies in this, the short ribs and gnocchi so tender and flavorful I'm drooling now.
But of course we ordered desserts that we couldn't finish and had to take with us as well lol. Tiramisu, cannoli and can't go without trying the Affogato this we did finish! We both loved the Affogato the best, vanilla bean ice cream and espresso can't go wrong there. The other's were good but just a little too sweet for me. We are definitely making a return visit, coming back for some Hobo Stew!!< /text>

< Review>
This is one of several fabulous restaurants in Carmel. Appetizers grilled artichoke and deep-fried artichoke lollipops were enjoyable. Entrees lamb shank osso buco, chiopino, ribeye steak, veal ravioli were all prepared and presented well. The menu is simple and covers the basics of Italian cuisine. < text>
This place is a nice little Carmel spot. When we came, we ordered two wines off the menu, a 2009 and a 2010. When they delivered a 2011 and 2012 respectively, we asked why they were different. They explained they were out of the ones we had ordered and they were going to charge the same price. <review>We stumbled across this quaint Italian restaurant 4 yrs ago. Now, it's our 1st stop as we arrive into town. They have THE BEST gnocchi that I've ever had-anywhere! In fact, I can't eat it anywhere else other than at Pepe's restaurants.  (He also has Vesuvio's in town.) Lil Napoli is warm, quaint, very friendly and you can rent their back room for a larger party/private meal and it has a fireplace too. Dogs are welcome if you sit outside. They sell a pre-made Manhatten  called "Doc Pepe's Lab" that I buy by the case.  That stuff is fantastic and all my guests take my bottle after they have 1 glass. <rating>5< /rating>< Text>
We stumbled across this quaint Italian restaurant 4 yrs ago. Now, it's our 1st stop as we arrive into town. They have THE BEST gnocchi that I've ever had-anywhere! In fact, I can't eat it anywhere else other than at Pepe's restaurants.  (He also has Vesuvio's in town.) Lil Napoli is warm, quaint, very friendly and you can rent their back room for a larger party/private meal and it has a fireplace too. Dogs are welcome if you sit outside. They sell a pre-made Manhatten  called "Doc Pepe's Lab" that I buy by the case.  That stuff is fantastic and all my guests take my bottle after they have 1 glass. Oh, super good chicken piccata, meatball appetizer,  garlic bread (over 100 yr old recipe)<//Text>

<GmapID>0x808de6150ec03e61:0x25c5355734227bb6< /GmapID><time>1283545680432</time><Name>Alex Gawley< /Name></record></dataset><record>
<rate>3< /rate><review>One of many Italian-oriented eateries in Carmel. Our experience didn't start too well - First off, there are too many entrances and only one wait station. Once you enter, the servers and the wait staff are rough around the edges to say the least (i.e. we were given lunch menus at 8pm...). Additionally, the tables are crammed next to each other. Besides that, it has a nice overall ambiance, with a beautiful interior and intimate lighting.

As for the food, the "famous" garlic bread ain't that great... Skip it. The menu is priced fairly, by Carmel standards. The time between appetizers and entrees took a while, granted it was a busy night. The tricolor cannelloni was mostly good (great pesto sauce on one of the thirds). The cioppino was very good, but was just a tad watery. Lasagna good and simple, and the calamari we had was excellent. Overall, i would say Little Napoli is middle of the road, but does warrant a visit.<//review>< user_name>

<Rate>3<//Rate>< Review>
Me and my husband ate pizza here (di parma and mushroom & combozola), and it was very so-so. It was OK, but I have made better at home; mushroom and combozola was better than di parma. The cutlery I was given was a fork and a butter knife, which was definitely not the ideal thing to cut the pizza with; I was sitting there and sawing each piece off for 15 seconds, which definitely took away from the experience. One of the other people we ere with had lasagna, and that too was just OK. The place was very busy and crowded, and there was a line through a part of the restaurant, right next to the tables. It's a bit strange having people standing right there, staring at your food while they wait, so I wish we had chosen a place that was less busy< /Review>

< text>
My husband and I stopped here for dinner recently.  They were very busy.  The hostess told us she could seat us at 8:30 and it was about 7.  I asked if there was seating available for us outside because I heard her say there was to the couple in front of us.  She said yes and seated us outside only after I asked.  We waited at least 20 minutes before anyone came to our table.  During those 20 minutes, other servers walked right past our table and didn't say a word to us.  It was really strange...not a single person welcoming us or bringing us glasses for the bottled water already on the table.  I actually made eye contact with a few servers, but they looked right past me.  When our waitress did come she could tell we were not happy.  She did bring us delicious garlic bread on the house because we had to wait so long, which we appreciated.   Our meals were simply wonderful.  I had the salmon and my husband the lasagna.  Our waitress came by during the meal 1 or 2 times to check on us.  But, then we didn't see her again.  I had to ask another waitress to please have our waitress bring us our tab.  Instead, the hostess came outside and took care of it.  She had the personality of a rock.  But, we would certainly give this restaurant a second chance because the food was amazing.<//text>

< review>
We arrived at little napoli at around 4pm on a Saturday and sat on the cafe side. It took awhile to be served, and there was a bit of a wait for our food to arrive. We ordered off the lunch menu, the portions and prices differ from the evening menu. I ordered the eggplant parmigiana, not a typical eggplant parm...2-slices of eggplant with cheese topping and red sauce, served with handmade noodles in white sauce, it was okay, not great. The pizza was good, and the Caesar salad was excellent. We paid the bill not paying too much attention to the total...however, as we were leaving it stuck my boyfriend that the bill was high for what we ordered. He asked to look at the menu and discovered we were charged the evening menu prices...$28 for a small portion of eggplant  parm instead of $18... We brought this mistake to our waiter‚Äôs attention. After discussing it with his manager he came back to inform us that it is dinner time now. We of course objected. Our waiter, along with another wait staff,  made a production out of refunding our money and re-billing us. Two-and-one-half hour‚Äôs later, when we returned to our hotel room, we discovered our waiter didn‚Äôt return our credit card after the second transaction. It was too late to call little napoli so we checked our credit card transactions. The last transaction was the over-charged bill from little napoli, they did not credit us for the over priced meal. The next day we called the Restaurant only to be met with a laxed attitude of indifference from the staff.  Poor customer service, average food. We will not be returning and we do not recommend little napoli. By the way we are Italians.<//review>

<Text>When visiting the Carmel area for the first time this summer, we were trying to figure out where to go for dinner.  We came upon this place, and yes - I am a fan of Little Napoli and I would return, but it was not INCREDIBLE, especially for what you would expect for these prices (I know - we are in an expensive area, but still, I expected INCREDIBLE). When consulting with online review sites to see whether or not to try Little Napoli, I noticed that garlic bread, one of my all-time favorite foods, was one of the most talked about things in the reviews, that pretty much made the decision for me to try this place.  I must say though, that I was kind of disappointed with the garlic bread because I have definitely had better at other places.  But, no garlic bread is bad enough not to, including this garlic bread, which was wolfed down shortly after receiving.  It was flavorful, but not to memorable.  Maybe it was the bread used that was off for me.  Anyway, the chicken parmesan I had for my main meal was 100% good and tasty, but like I said, for the price, I expected to be blown away like, "Wow! This is one of the best chicken parmesans I've ever had!" but I unfortunately didn't experience that.  The staff by the way were great.  At no time did I have any issues with them so I give the waiters, waitresses, hostesses and everyone else 5 stars!  Lastly, we got to the dessert.  Were the desserts good? Yes! Were they the best I'd had ever had? No :( One of the desserts we got (yes we got multiple desserts - don't judge me!) was the cannoli which I can was indeed unique and interesting was that the cream inside was chocolaty - yum! Now, I don't want you to think that I'm being too negative of unfair with my review, but I guess there was just something missing or nothing stuck out as being over the top memorable and delicious, but that's okay and remember, this place is a solid four stars and I encourage you to go and try it for yourself - and treat yourself to the garlic bread to see what you think!< /Text><gmapID>0x808de6150ec03e61:0x25c5355734227bb6</gmapID>< Response>

<Review>This is a nice little Italian restaurant in the heart of Carmel. It has nice decorations. The service was outstanding. Cristina & other staff were extremely helpful in identifying what was vegetarian - the bread was made with egg, but their mozzarella was animal rennet free. We were underwhelmed by the food. Both napoletana pizzas were ok - cooked too well, & again fortifying Una Pizza Napoletana in San Francisco as the best napoletana pizza. But the service, ambience & concern for our dietary concerns more than made up for the food. Next time, we may come back here.< /Review>< Pictures>
